<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910422-0032</DOCNO><DOCID>910422-0032.</DOCID><HL>   Bridgestone Unit Reaches   3-Year Pact With Workers</HL><DATE>04/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C16</SO><CO>   F.MIC GT J.BDT LABOR</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>AUTO PARTS AND EQUIPMENT INCLUDING TIRES (AUP)</IN><NS>LABOR, PERSONNEL ISSUES, TRENDS, MANAGEMENT TECHNIQUES (LAB)</NS><RE>FRANCE (FR)JAPAN (JA)OHIO (OH)</RE><LP>   Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. reached a new three-year laboragreement with the United Rubber Workers, setting a patternfor some 35,000 workers throughout the American tireindustry.   The agreement in principle, reached just before themidnight Saturday deadline, covers 5,000 workers at theBridgestone Corp. unit. URW negotiators are now discussingthe contract with negotiators for Goodyear Tire andamp; Rubber Co.and Groupe Michelin's Uniroyal Goodrich Tire Co. Bothcompanies, which have extended the current contract on aday-to-day basis, are expected to reach a similar agreementcovering 18,000 workers in the coming days. The pattern isalso likely to be adopted for an additional 12,000 workers atsmaller tire companies in the coming months.</LP><TEXT>   Negotiators for both sides declined to discuss specificdetails before the final language has been reached. However,sources close to the negotiations said the agreement providesan overall increase of 18% over the previous contract, in acombination of wages, pensions and benefits. The sources saidthe union won significant improvement in pensions and was notforced into any givebacks.   A Bridgestone/Firestone spokesman said the company was&quot;pleased&quot; and called the contract a &quot;win-win&quot; settlement. Theagreement is subject to rank-and-file approval.   Under the just-expired contract, tire workers have anaverage hourly wage of $15.47 and average benefits equal to$12.12 an hour.</TEXT></DOC>